the public when they perceive that their stand has widespread popular support, he also shows that there are many important and revealing exceptions to this pattern. Kollman develops his theory of outside lobbying through a combination of rational choice modeling and statistical tests that compare public opinion data with data from his interviews about interest groups' policy positions and activities. The tests reveal that group leaders use outside lobbying to take advantage of pre-existing public preferences, not to recruit members or to try to generate the mere appearance of grass-roots support. Kollman's innovative book will clarify the complex relationship among lobbying, public opinion, and public policy, and will set a new standard for interest group research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  a3M Corporation.  aAmerican Petroleum Institute.  aBanks, Jeffrey.  aBonner and Associates.  aBusiness Roundtable.  aChaffee plan.  aClinton, Bill.  aDonnelly, Brian (D-MA).  aEndangered Species Act.  aExxon Corporation.  aFirst Amendment.  aGeneral Motors Corporation.  aGray Panthers.  aGreenpeace USA.  aJews.  aJones, Brian.  aKernell, Samuel.  aKingdon, John.  aLTV Corporation.  aMoe, Terry.  aOlson, Mancur.  aUnited We Stand.  aWall Street Journal.  aWeingast, Barry.  aZero Population Growth.  aagenda-shaping stage.  aconflict expansion.  acoordination problems.  adirect mail fundraising.  afactor analysis.  afocal points.  aframing.  ahat trick story.  ahealth care.  ainside lobbying.  aintensity dilemma.  alogit analysis.  amail to Congress.  amass media.  aneed for action stage.  apersuasion theory.  apopularity.  apress conferences.  areferendums.  aresource mobilization th